anisms within academic publishing systems.\",52\r\n294,AUTHORSHIP,DISCLOSURE,\"The AUTHORSHIP and DISCLOSURE guidelines in academic publishing emphasize the importance of transparency by requiring authors to disclose the use of AI technology and AI tools in their work. These requirements are consistently stated across the descriptions, highlighting that authors must report the integration of artificial intelligence into their research processes, including the specific AI tools employed. Such disclosure ensures accountability, maintains academic integrity, and supports the ethical use of AI in scholarly output. The focus on both \"\"AI technology\"\" and \"\"AI tools\"\" underscores a broad yet precise approach to ensuring that all forms of AI involvement in research are made explicit to readers and reviewers.\",51\r\n187,PEER REVIEWER,DISCLOSURE,\"Peer reviewers must disclose the use of AI tools in their evaluations to maintain transparency, as this requirement is emphasized in both descriptions provided. The disclosure ensures that the review process remains open and accountable, allowing stakeholders to assess the potential influence of artificial intelligence on the evaluation outcomes. This practice aligns with broader efforts to integrate ethical and transparent standards into academic publishing, particularly in the context of AI governance. The entity \"\"PEER REVIEWER\"\" is central to this process, while \"\"DISCLOSURE\"\" represents the key procedural requirement that supports integrity and trust within the academic ecosystem.\",50\r\n157,EDITOR,DISCLOSURE,\"The Editor plays a central role in enforcing policies that require authors to disclose the use of AI tools in their manuscripts. This disclosure requirement extends to the submission and peer review process, where Editors may actively request information about AI usage to ensure transparency and adherence to ethical standards. The concept of Disclosure is integral to this process, as it underpins the expectations for accountability and clarity regarding the role of artificial intelligence in academic research. Together, the Editor and the principle of Disclosure shape the governance framework within academic publishing, ensuring that AI-generated content is appropriately acknowledged and evaluated.\",48\r\n197,JOURNAL,DISCLOSURE,\"The JOURNAL, such as JOLE, requires authors to disclose the use of AI tools in their submissions, including both the cover letter and the manuscript itself. This disclosure requirement is part of the DISCLOSURE policies implemented by the JOURNAL to ensure transparency in the use of artificial intelligence technologies in academic research and writing processes. These policies aim to uphold ethical standards and provide clarity regarding the role of AI in scholarly work.\",47\r\n93,LLM,DISCLOSURE,Large Language Models must be disclosed when used in manuscript preparation,43\r\n318,DISCLOSURE,EMERALD,\"Emerald requires authors to disclose the use of AI technology in their submissions, ensuring transparency\",42\r\n85,LANGUAGE MODEL,DISCLOSURE,Language models must be disclosed when used in manuscript preparation,40\r\n330,DISCLOSURE,ACADEMIC PUBLISHING,Academic publishing processes require authors to disclose the use of AI tools in their work,38\r\n325,DISCLOSURE,CITATION,\"Authors must cite sources properly, including AI-generated content, to maintain transparency\",36\r\n314,SUBMISSION,PEER REVIEW PROCESS,The peer review process may require authors to disclose the use of AI tools in their submissions,36\r\n326,DISCLOSURE,SOURCE,\"Authors must disclose the source of all content, including AI-generated material, to ensure transparency\",35\r\n328,DISCLOSURE,WILEY,Wiley requires authors to disclose the use of AI technology upon submission,34\r\n322,DISCLOSURE,AI-GENERATED CONTENT,\"AI-generated content must be disclosed and cited appropriately, similar to other external sources\",33\r\n317,DISCLOSURE,DUP,\"DUP requires authors to disclose 